That message is the API returning **403 FORBIDDEN** after JWT authorization: the client id in the URL must be allowed by your bearer token.

### What the API checks

For `/api/v1/clients/:clientId/memories`, the `preHandler` runs `enforceClientScopeAuthorization`, which requires:

1. A **`practice_id`** claim on the JWT.
2. The path **`clientId`** to be in the token’s client scope: the **`client_id`** claim plus any UUIDs in **`client_ids`**.

```314:464:c:\Users\Ken Levy\OneDrive\Documents\Business\Ohana\Memories\apps\api\src\app.ts
function readClientScope(payload: JWTPayload): Set<string> {
  const scope = new Set<string>();
  const focalClientId = readStringClaim(payload, "client_id");
  if (focalClientId) {
    scope.add(focalClientId);
  }

  for (const clientId of readStringArrayClaim(payload, "client_ids")) {
    scope.add(clientId);
  }

  return scope;
}
// ...
  const clientScope = readClientScope(request.auth);
  if (clientScope.size === 0 || !clientScope.has(targetClientId)) {
    logAuthzDenied(request, "client_scope_mismatch", targetClientId, memoryIdPresent);
    throw new HttpError(
      403,
      "FORBIDDEN",
      "Insufficient permissions for requested resource.",
    );
  }
```

So **`00000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001`** only works if that UUID is in the token’s scope. With the stock **`npm run dev:local-auth`** token, it is not.

### What the dev token actually allows

The local helper mints a fixed **`client_id`**:

```15:20:c:\Users\Ken Levy\OneDrive\Documents\Business\Ohana\Memories\apps\api\scripts\local-auth-dev.ts
const DEFAULT_CLAIMS = {
  user_id: "a6ba3030-d9ca-42f7-8c8e-e6ec4c478200",
  practice_id: "4ef4febe-b026-439d-abd9-d6477b4870f6",
  client_id: "8f9512d8-e88f-4f82-a8e9-6cb19a43ad52",
  roles: ["GUIDE"],
} as const;
```

The web home screen default is only a UI placeholder:

```214:222:c:\Users\Ken Levy\OneDrive\Documents\Business\Ohana\Memories\apps\web\src\app\router.tsx
const DEFAULT_HOME_CLIENT_ID = "00000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001";

function HomePage() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  const { configured: firebaseConfigured, user: firebaseUser, loading, defaultClientId } =
    useFirebaseSession();
  const [clientIdOverride, setClientIdOverride] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const clientId =
    (clientIdOverride ?? defaultClientId ?? DEFAULT_HOME_CLIENT_ID).trim() || DEFAULT_HOME_CLIENT_ID;
```

### What to do for manual v0.5 dev testing

1. Keep **`dev:local-auth`** running and paste the token from `http://127.0.0.1:3010/dev/token` into the web app as usual.
2. On the home “Open a client workspace” field, use **`8f9512d8-e88f-4f82-a8e9-6cb19a43ad52`** (or open  
   `http://localhost:5173/clients/8f9512d8-e88f-4f82-a8e9-6cb19a43ad52/memories` directly).

Using **`00000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001`** with that token will keep producing **`client_scope_mismatch`** in API logs and the **Insufficient permissions** message in the UI—that’s expected, not a broken list endpoint.

If you want the default home id to match local-auth without editing the helper, we could align `DEFAULT_HOME_CLIENT_ID` with `DEFAULT_CLAIMS.client_id` in a small follow-up change (say the word if you want that).

